comments.author: @deathmetal8259
comments.text:
The worst part is this guy never even made it to the actual competition part. This is as far as he got. They handed out 24 aprons, but only selected 18 people for television. If you look up the season 2 list of contestants, he's not on the list, but the episode he was on was episode 2, which was an audition episode.

Now it's anecdotal evidence, but an old friend of mine actually participated in shows like this before MasterChef hit the airwaves. His dishes would wow the judges, but if you didn't have a story for the production team to sell on TV, you never made it to the airwaves. Hell, you didn't even get a chance to interact with the judges afterwards to get tips, tricks or even job offers. It was a "thanks for the food, there's the door" type of deal.
